{{Infobox presenter | name = Carol Off | image = Carol Off - Eden Mills Writers Festival - 2017 (DanH-1333) (cropped).jpg | alt = Carol Off at the Eden Mills Writers Festival in 2017 | caption = Off at the [[Eden Mills Writers' Festival]] in 2017 | native_name = | native_name_lang = | birth_name = | birth_date = <!-- {{Birth date and age|1993|2|24|df=yes}} --> | birth_place = | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|1993|2|24|df=yes}} --> | death_place = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = | alma_mater = [[University of Western Ontario]] | show = ''[[As It Happens]]'' | station = | network = [[CBC Radio One]] | timeslot = | show2 = | station2 = | network2 = | timeslot2 = | style = | country = | prevshow = | parents = | spouse(s) = [[Linden MacIntyre]] (m. 2000) | partner = | children = | memorials = | website = | module = }}
'''Carol Off''' is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] journalist, commentator, and author associated with [[CBC Television]] and [[CBC Radio]].
==Career== Off has been a host of [[CBC Radio One]]'s ''[[As It Happens]]'' since 2006.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/arts/story/2006/05/18/aih-host-off.html CBC journalist Carol Off to host 'As It Happens']. [[CBC News]], May 18, 2006.</ref> Previously a [[documentary film|documentary]] reporter for ''[[The National (CBC)|The National]]'', Off also hosted the political debate series ''[[counterSpin (TV series)|counterSpin]]'' on [[CBC Newsworld]].
She was part of the board of directors of [[Canadian Journalists for Free Expression]] from 2001 to 2007.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cjfe.org/cjfe_gala_chair_carol_off_interviewed_by_george_stroumboulopoulos|title=CJFE Gala Chair Carol Off interviewed by George Stroumboulopoulos|work=CJFE {{!}} Canadian Journalists for Free Expression|access-date=2017-06-12}}</ref> She was awarded [[ACTRA]]'s [[John Drainie Award]], for distinguished contributions to Canadian broadcasting, in 2008.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/story/2008/07/31/actra-off-medal.html CBC journalist Carol Off wins broadcasting award]. [[CBC News]], July 31, 2008.</ref>
Off has also written several books on the Canadian military, including ''[[The Lion, the Fox, and the Eagle]]'' (2000) and ''The Ghosts of Medak Pocket: the Story of Canada's Secret War'' (2005, {{ISBN|0-679-31294-3}}). In 2006, she released a book, ''Bitter Chocolate'', about the corruption and human rights abuses associated with the [[Cocoa bean|cocoa]] industry. She wrote that French-Canadian journalist [[Guy-André Kieffer]], who was kidnapped in [[Abidjan]], [[Côte d'Ivoire]] in 2004, had been murdered for exposing Ivorian government corruption in connection with cocoa.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.su.ualberta.ca/mainpage_content/news/20061106_CarolOff |date=2006-11-11 |accessdate=2007-08-25 |title=Chocolate a product of child slavery, says CBC broadcaster |publisher=Revolutionary Speaker Series, University of Alberta Student's Union |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080523092306/http://www.su.ualberta.ca/mainpage_content/news/20061106_CarolOff |archivedate=2008-05-23 |df= }}</ref>
Off grew up in [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usc.uwo.ca/gazette/2000/November/23/Arts_and_Entertainment1.htm |title=Grad returns with book - The Lion, the fox, the eagle and Carol Off |publisher=Western Gazette |date=November 23, 2000 |first=Colin |last=Butler |accessdate=October 30, 2014 }}</ref> She got her start in journalism as a staff writer for ''The Gazette'', the student newspaper at [[The University of Western Ontario]]. She graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] degree from Western in 1981.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://communications.uwo.ca/com/western_news/stories/alumni_awards_of_merit_-_2009_20091001444911/ |title=Alumni Awards of Merit - 2009 |publisher=Western News |date=October 1, 2009 |first=Karmen |last=Dowling |accessdate=October 30, 2014 }}</ref>
==Personal life== Off married fellow CBC broadcaster [[Linden MacIntyre]] in 2000.
