[[File:Origine della Compagnia della Misericordia in Firenze.jpg|thumb|The body of a dead woman is brought before the [[Gonfaloniere of Justice]] in Florence in 1425, the legendary origin of the ''Compagnia della Misericordia'']] The '''Gonfalonier''' (in Italian: ''Gonfaloniere'') was the holder of a highly prestigious [[Medieval commune|communal]] office in [[Italy in the Middle Ages|medieval]] and [[Italian Renaissance|Renaissance Italy]], notably in [[Florence]] and the [[Papal States]].<ref>{{cite book | title=Archivio delle Tratte: Introduzione e inventario | publisher=Rome: Archivio di Stato di Firenze |author1=Viti, Paolo |author2=Zaccaria, Raffaella Maria | year=1989}}</ref> The name derives from ''[[gonfalone]]'' (in English, gonfalon), the term used for the banners of such communes.
In Florence, the office was known as [[Gonfalonier of Justice]] (''Gonfaloniere di Giustizia'') and was held by one of the nine citizens selected by the drawing lots every two months, who formed the city's government, or [[Signoria of Florence|Signoria]].{{citation needed|date=August 2013}} In the papal states, it was known as [[Gonfalonier of the Church]] or Papal Gonfalonier.<ref name="BritannicaGonfalonier">{{cite web | url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/238447/gonfalonier | title=Gonfalonier: Medieval Italian Official | publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica | date=23 November 2014 | accessdate=2 May 2015}}</ref> Other central and northern Italian communes, from [[Spoleto]] to the [[County of Savoy]], elected or appointed ''gonfalonieri.'' The [[House of Bentivoglio|Bentivoglio family]] of [[Bologna]] aspired to this office during the sixteenth century. However, by the year 1622, when [[Artemisia Gentileschi]] painted a portrait of [[Pietro Gentile]] as a gonfaloniere of [[Bologna]], with the ''gonfalone'' in the background, the office had merely symbolic value.
==See also== *[[Capitano del popolo]] *[[Condottieri]] *[[Gonfalonier of the Church]] *[[Podestà]]
