{{for|the architect and antiquarian|John Newman (architect)}} {{Use British English|date=July 2013}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}} {{Infobox person | name = John Newman | honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MA|FSA|size=100%}} | image = | caption = | birth_name = John Arthur Newman | birth_date = {{birth year and age|1936|12}} | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | resting_place = | nationality = British | other_names = | education = | alma_mater = [[Dulwich College]], [[Oxford University]], [[Courtauld Institute of Art]] | occupation = [[Art historian|Architectural historian]] | notable_works = ''[[The Buildings of England]]'', ''[[The Buildings of Wales]]'' | children = | parents = | relatives = | awards = | website= | spouse = }} '''John Arthur Newman''' (born December 1936)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yalebooksblog.co.uk/2012/10/03/author-blog-john-newman-on-architecture-and-aging/ |title=Author Article: John Newman on Architecture and Aging - Yale University Press London Blog |publisher=Yalebooksblog.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2017-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/p272mouDROAkYi2p-DWLEomno4o/appointments |title=John Arthur NEWMAN |publisher=Companies House |date= |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref> is an English architectural historian.{{sfn|Newman|2001|p=cover}} He is the author of several of the [[Pevsner Architectural Guides]] and is the advisory editor to the series.
Newman<ref>{{cite web|title=John Arthur Newman : a bibliography of books, papers, selected reviews and miscellanea|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/john-arthur-newman-a-bibliography-of-books-papers-selected-reviews-and-miscellanea/oclc/886966023|website=OCLC|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref> was born in 1936, and has lived most of his life in [[Kent]]. He was educated at [[Dulwich College]] and [[Oxford University]] where he read [[Greats]] (classics). In 1959 he became a classics teacher at [[Tonbridge School]]. In 1963 he left his teaching post to study for a diploma in the history of European art at the [[Courtauld Institute of Art]], which he passed with distinction. In 1966 he was appointed a full-time assistant lecturer at the Courtauld, where he taught until his retirement.<ref name=Higgott>{{cite journal|last1=Higgott|first1=Gordon|title=John Newman: An Appreciation|journal=Architectural History|date=2001|volume=44|page=1|doi=10.2307/1568726}} [https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/architectural-history/article/john-newman-an-appreciation/62D22BC0CF6FBBE1693FCE8B293BB2F2 ''abstract]</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kauffmann|first1=Michael|title=John Newman at the Courtauld Institute|journal=Architectural History|date=2001|volume=44|page=5|doi=10.2307/1568727}} [https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/architectural-history/article/john-newman-at-the-courtauld-institute/70B7D640F7CD45E39AC078C82F149B60# ''abstract'']</ref>{{sfn|Newman|2001|p=cover}}
While a student at the Courtauld, Newman acted as driver to [[Nikolaus Pevsner]] for five weeks in Hampshire. Pevsner suggested that Newman should research and write the architectural guides on Kent, which were published in 1969.<ref name=Higgott/> Newman worked with Pevsner on ''The Buildings of England'' series,{{sfn|Newman|2001|p=cover}} which has been expanded as the ''[[Pevsner Architectural Guides]]'' to cover Scotland, Wales and Ireland. Since 1983, Newman has acted as the advisory editor to the series.{{sfn|Newman|2001|p=cover}} Bridget Cherry, the general editor of the series, and author of a history of the project, describes Newman as the most significant of Pevsner's collaborators,{{sfn|Cherry|1983|p=8}} and Pevsner himself considered Newman's two volumes on [[Kent]] to be "the best of the whole series".{{sfn|Cherry|1983|p=8}}
From 1975 to 1985 Newman was honorary editor of the journal ''[[Architectural History (journal)|Architectural History]]''.<ref name=Higgott/> He has served on the executive committee of the Society of Architectural Historians of Great Britain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sahgb.org.uk/uploads/1/9/5/2/1952873/7.pdf |title=Society of Architectural Historians of Great Britain |publisher= |date= |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref> In 1986 Newman chaired the Pevsner Memorial Trust, which undertook the restoration of the [[murals]] at the [[Church of St Michael and All Angels, Garton on the Wolds|Church of St Michael and All Angels]], [[Garton on the Wolds]], [[East Riding of Yorkshire]] in memory of Sir Nikolaus.{{sfn|Bradley|Cherry|2001|p=76}}
==Publications== * ''[[Pevsner Architectural Guides|The Buildings of England]]'' : Dorset (1972) (with Nikolaus Pevsner)<ref name="yalebooks1">{{cite web|url=http://yalebooks.co.uk/results.asp?NAT=false&sort=%24rank&SF1=keyword&ST1=John+Newman |title= The Buildings of England & Wales |publisher= Yale University Press|date= |accessdate=2017-03-27}}</ref> : Kent - West and the Weald (2012)<ref name="yalebooks1"/> : Kent - North East and East (2013)<ref name="yalebooks1"/> : Shropshire (2006)<ref name="yalebooks1"/>
* ''[[Pevsner Architectural Guides|The Buildings of Wales]]'' : Glamorgan (1995)<ref name="yalebooks1"/> : Gwent/Monmouthshire (2000)<ref name="yalebooks1"/>
