[[File:Aigle_de_Suger.jpg|thumb|Suger's Eagle on display in the Louvre]]
'''Suger's Eagle''' (''Aigle de Suger'') is an [[Art of ancient Egypt|ancient Egyptian]] [[Porphyry (geology)|porphyry]] [[vase]] mounted in a [[Middle Ages|medieval]] [[silver-gilt]] eagle.{{sfn|Verdier|1990|p=13}} It is now displayed along with the [[French regalia]] in the [[Galerie d'Apollon]] at the [[Louvre]].{{sfn|Verdier|1990|p=23}}

The vase likely dates to the second century <small>AD</small>.{{sfn|Heckscher|1938|p=216 n. 3|ps=, citing [[Suger's_Eagle#CITEREFDelbrück1932|Delbrück 1932]], p. 203}} According to [[Suger]], abbot of [[Saint-Denis Abbey|Saint-Denis]], in his  ''De administratione'', he found, "lying idly in a chest for many years, an Egyptian porphyry vase admirably shaped and polished."{{sfn|Verdier|1990|p=13}} In his own words, he determined to adapt and transfer (''adaptavimus ... transferre'') it into a liturgical vessel "in the form of an eagle" (''in aquilae formam''), a symbol of Christ.{{sfn|Heckscher|1938|pp=216–17}} Suger's Eagle is a typical case of the "careful preservation of the ancient relic in a setting which leaves it completely intact."{{sfn|Heckscher|1938|pp=216–17}} On the bottom of the eagle is a [[niello]]ed ''[[Titulus (inscription)|titulus]]'': "This stone deserves to have mounts of gold and gems. / It was marble. Its settings are more precious than marble."{{sfn|Verdier|1990|p=13}} Inscribed around the base of the neck, above the lip of the vessel, is a dedication to the church of Saint-Denis.{{sfn|Heckscher|1938|pp=216–17}} The [[Goldsmith|goldwork]] of the neck demonstrates superb chiselwork.{{sfn|Stratford|1981|p=509}}

Two large engravings from 1706 depict the treasure of Saint-Denis (including the eagle vase) as it was then displayed, in a cabinet. Its popularity as a tourist attraction prevented the treasure's total destruction during the [[French Revolution]].{{sfn|Stratford|1991|pp=337–38}} The eagle and three of Suger's other liturgical vessels—Queen Eleanor's vase and King Roger's decanter, both of rock crystal, and a sardonyx ewer—ended up in the Galerie d'Apollon at the Louvre.{{sfn|Verdier|1990|p=23}}

